values: I became aware of the pain and numbness of my lower back against the toilet seat. It was time to move on. The thing was in my hands. Terrified to look at it, I knew the answer. When the courage finally summoned, the two lines pierced through me. Them being there was no surprise - I was late, I was sick every morning after drinking my espresso. But that didn’t matter to the tears. What was I to do? I was sixteen. Just. I had to go to school the next morning. I leaned over to pick up another one from the floor. It had two lines as well. Mum and dad couldn’t know, dad would have thrown me out of the house if he found out! That week was bitter sweet. Every day the housemaid, the only adult who knew, looked at me and cried. She prayed for us. My showers were full of stroking, talking, imagining it grow. That was a strange feeling – not being alone, having someone else being part of me, someone I was responsible for – a responsibility I couldn’t fulfill. That magical someone breathed and moved inside me. Its little soul hovered by my side. And, through tears, I whispered that everything would be okay, that this was its lesson here on Earth this time round and that there would be another time when we meet and perhaps live a longer, happier life together. I whispered I would always love and remember no matter what; and the water hid the whispers and the tears from my parents. Classes were full of exchanging notes with my two girl friends, planning. They were the ones to miss a class with me to go see a doctor. “What do I do?” I asked the doctor. “You should have thought of it before,” she said. And so we found a different doctor, one who accepted money for an under-aged patient without parental concern. The last day of the week, before our classes, I smoked a cigarette and one of my girl friends said that I wasn’t supposed to be smoking in my condition. And the other one told her to shut up. And then they went to school and I walked to the bus stop. There was a robe and a sanitary towel in my bag, as instructed. I found blood stuck to the inside of my thighs when I woke up. It seemed someone shouted my name from the hospital yard outside the window, but there was no one there. The doctor brought me an apple. She told me I had slept longer after the anesthesia than the others. There were nine other women in the hospital room with me. Most of them went after me, but they all awoke first and now awaited me with curiosity. They wanted to know why. I had nothing to tell them - they all were mothers of many and only in the same room with me because there was something wrong with their fetuses. And so I got dressed and left. The nurses said I needed to rest, but there was only one hour left before the end of the classes. I got off the bus and walked into the school. The bell rang and my two girl friends met me outside the classroom door. Together we walked out of school, kissed each other goodbye and I got into my mum’s car. “How was your day?” she asked. “It was okay,” I answered.

My dear friends, brace yourselves. It will be a long ride. Got your seat belts on? Okay then, let's roll... 

Maybe it's just me, but words "religious" and "hatred" don't sound like they could stand next to each other when we are talking about feelings of a religious person. The main reason for my humble opinion is that such combination in itself would be a contradiction of what most organised religions preach and definitely a contradiction for a spiritually intelligent being. And yet, one of the core legal arguments against the Pussy Riot was that this group promoted feminism, which by itself ignites a "religious hatred" in the souls of the Russian Christians...

Was this the only absurdity in the Pussy Riot judgement?



So the girls have defiled the cathedral. According to the witnesses (cathedral employees and religious visitors), this was especially done by shouting offences to the names of God and His Holiness the Patriarch himself. This is according to the witnesses. These same witnesses stated in court that they had not heard any political slogans in the girls' words,and thus regard girls' act as solely anti-religious. Now the interesting bit: these same witnesses have stated that all they had witnessed was how five (yes, five, only three caught) girls were screaming SOME words, chaotically waving their arms and legs and dancing... Oh, but the witnesses' feelings did manage to get hurt; witnesses had made sure the court heard this point better than what the witnesses themselves heard on the day of the riot.

Were the girls attacking God? Witnesses managed to figure out one clear statement from girls' mouths: "Holy Mother, become feminist!" To me, calling this an attack on God is a paradox. As one of the Pussy Riot girls pointed out, should the Holy Mother enter any Christian church or cathedral, she would not be allowed into the Altar because she is not a man... Now THAT is an attack on God! 

Perhaps, they were attacking His So-Called-Holiness? Oh yes, very much so. Moreover, one of the Pussy Riot girls was so opened about it, she even talked about this in court! And why shouldn't she? If His So-Called-Holiness allowed himself to call his congregation to vote for Putin, stating that Putin's political power is from God, than what holy is there to respect in His Holiness? May I remind you that the riot itself took place on 21February 2012, before Putin (now nick-named - by group Femen - Pussyn) was "elected" for the third time? The riot was directed at showing opposition to the prediction of Pussyn becoming a President and Medvedev becoming a Vice on 4 March 2012...

Well, perhaps this would be the end of the ludicrousness? Oh no, the judges had almost 3 hours to embarrass themselves while reading out their judgement! 

So the judges were not ashamed to read out loud the legal psychological-psychiatrical expert statements that called Pussy Riot girls sufferers of mixed personality disorder. The following was stated as evidence for this disorder: active life position, relying on personal experience in decision-making process, aims of self-realisation with standing up for social values that are overvalued in their significance and distinctiveness of interests, self-confidence... and so on, and so on... I kid you not, this is my word-for-word translation. The state of the disorder was not regarded to be serious enough to argue that girls did not understand what they were doing on the day of the riot, and  no necessity for the mental hospitalisation was found [yet], so the prison sentence remains intact.

What can I say? Of course girls must be mad! Why else would they say that the given cathedral is not a House of God, a place of a spiritual life, but an office, even a business centre, with its own banquet halls that are rented out for money, its own laundry room and guarded carpark?

Source - judgement, full text in Rus at http://www.bg.ru/stories/11662/

PS: Just like word "holy" is turned head down in our upside-down world, a law provision protecting Russians against someone who wants to ignite hatred is also upside down... A guy who publicly shared a video against skinheads (who are a big problem in Russia as they literary beat up and slaughter non-Russians and non-traditionally looking Russians) was accused yesterday (20.08.2012) in igniting hatred towards nationalistically-oriented citizens of Russian Federation. Is this paradox? Not in a land where thugs have ruled on every level of everyday lives for the past century; not in a country where every one, including toddlers, knows and speaks prison slang. 

PS2: You should hear what Russians are bubbling on about gay rights! Perhaps I'll do another article on that one day ;)

PS3: Shhh, don't tell anyone, but I think I might have a mixed personality disorder.................

Hey guys!

It's a regular evening out here. And as such, it brings memories... I think I might have said this before, but it's worth repeating: if I was a ghost, I would hunt the same place for centuries... I can't let go. It is all too tempting to relieve the past experience, to re-taste the sensations (especially the smell and the visual), to re-feel the emotions... Tonight its Khmelnitsky. It's about walking our town's hidden roads to smoke a cigarette unseen. It's about sharing the most important story of your life with a friend - a new story every day... It's about passing a piece of ice like a ball with a classmate. It's about stepping off a balcony on a ninth floor.....onto another balcony, of course. It's also about that split of a second when a thought "what if" storms through your mind while your foot is in the air between the two balconies. It's about fooling with a friend, pretending to be drunk, thinking that we are not really drunk, when, in fact, we are drunk... It's about running into your teacher on the school steps when you are just about to run away from their class... and not stopping, not coming back for class... and not getting in trouble for it, too! It's about being on duty in a cafeteria or rehearsing for a school play. It's about first best friend. It's about first love. It's about first... everything, almost everything. 

I might have reinvented myself a million times since, but tonight I've sat with you in a street cafe; I've walked with you into a computer shop; I've watched a train pass by with you by my side... 

I miss you. Tonight and always.

Billy was a thirty-years-old accountant. Who he really wanted to be was a street graffiti artist. So he went to a shop and bought himself a red spray paint. At night, when the town fell asleep and only few streetlights hovered in the dark, Billy went out to the seaside promenade and wrote his name on the pavement.

The morning crowd gathered around the red paint under their feet. “This is horrible,” – a woman in a yellow hat said. “Tasteless,” – her husband agreed. “Even I could do better than that,” – a kid told his sister. “Against the law,” – a policeman said and ordered for the pavement to be cleared. 

Billy ran home and hid under his duvet. “It’s okay,” – he thought: “Maybe I’m just not cut out to be a street graffiti artist.” Immediately he felt better. The thought that he didn’t have to be an artist lifted the burden off his whole being. He no longer felt obliged to achieve something he wasn’t sure he could. No more was there a sense of guilt for not doing something as good as others could – he simply was not an artist.

Thinking these comforting thoughts, Billy doze off and saw a dream. In that dream, he was eighty years old. He lived in a house with a garden and had two dogs. And he was wondering about what could have happened if only he hadn’t given up fifty years ago. In his dream, Billy knew that this thought had inhabited his mind every evening, just like an idea to become an artist came to him that one day he bought his first and only spray paint.

As soon as Billy woke, he ran to his computer and googled “street art”. He found names, techniques, works, inspiration and tools. And, hope found him. That night he went to the promenade again, armed with the red spray.

The morning crowd wondered about the name “Phillip” on the pavement. “Who’s Phillip?” – a man with glasses on his lean nose asked. “I’m Phillip,” – a small boy standing next to him said. “Vandalism,” – a policewoman said. “At least it is better drawn than yesterday,” – a teenager said. 

Billy ran home, smiling. On his way he got five more spray paints of different colours.

Throughout my life I have repeatedly grabbed my own ears and dragged myself out of politics. Why? Here are two main reasons:

1)    I cannot change anything.

2)    One who wants to fight will always find something to fight about.

To the question “why do you bother even though [1] and [2]? “ my friends replied: “because I am so sick of it I can no longer take it” and/or “because you might not be interested in war, but the war might be interested in you”.

And you know what? My friends were right, it IS unbearable and the war IS interested in YOU. Wake up! Whether voluntarily or forced, YOU are a slave. Nothing has changed since the medieval times: the strongest rule, the weakest pay.

Some time back in the cold winter months early in the year 2012 I had decided to learn knitting. So I bought two rolls of pure wool yarn, one white and one grey. “I’d like to knit something for you, like a scarf or a hat, what would you like?” - I asked my friend. “A summer vest,” - my friend replied. “White or grey?” - I asked. “Black,” – my friend answered. Okay, I had to get another roll of yarn, a black one this time. “Not a big deal, right?” - I thought.


I got on the Internet and found a number of summer vest designs with schemes of how to make them. There was only one problem: none of them were to be knitted; all of them were to be crocheted… “Are you sure you want a summer vest?” - I asked. “Positive,” – my friend answered. Okay, so I had to learn to crochet before I moved onto knitting. “No biggie,” - I thought.

I packed my friend into my car and drove to a local shop, the best in the city (or so I then thought), to look for a thin black cotton yarn and a right-sized steel crochet hook.
“There must be some mistake,” - the shop assistant told me: “the crochet hook is too small, the yarn is too thin, you can’t make a vest out of this!”
“Really?” - I asked.
“Well, you probably can, but it would take you forever, and it definitely won’t be ready for this summer, unless you spend days and nights crocheting non-stop…” – she answered.
“Oh,” – I said.
“And you have never crocheted before?” – she confirmed.
“No,” – I answered.
“Hm,” – she said. “We still have the right sized yarn,” – she offered.
“Really?” – I asked.
“Yeah! Which colour do you need?” – she replied.
“Black,” – I said.
“Oh, we don’t have black,” – she declared, “but we have ten other colours.”
“Okay, do you like any of these other colours?” – I turned to my friend: “A navy blue perhaps?” – I offered.
“Black or I’m not wearing it,” – my friend stated.
“Right,” – I turned back to the shop assistant: “Do you at least have a steel hook of the right size?”
“Only plastic,” – she replied. “Don’t bother,” – she added: “No one would appreciate it anyway!”

We got back into the car. “I don’t think I can crochet a summer vest for you,” – I confessed. “That’s okay. You are still my friend,” – my friend replied.

Later on that day I was in my bed with the cat on my knees and a cup of tea in my hands, surfing through the net. And then it hit me! Somebody out there had crocheted a summer vest! And they had used a thin cotton yarn and a small-sized crochet hook. So why was I so convinced by the shop assistant that I couldn’t do it? Was it just because I had never crocheted in my life? Or was it because they didn’t have the right colour of the yarn in the shop?

So I got onto Internet and found an online shop selling a thin black cotton yarn and the right-sized steel crochet hook. Three days later, they were on my doorstep. “Pick the design, I’m crocheting it!” – I called my friend whilst searching for crochet instruction videos on youtube.

I had to start over about five times before someone else showed me what I was doing wrong. It was mid-April by then. But I had finally learned, and, eventually, after I had started all over again that day in mid April 2012, I was able to present my friend with the final and fully completed version of the summer vest on Thursday 21st of June, year 2012. Since it was too cold in England to wear it yet, my friend had hanged it on the wall as a portrait and I was now welcomed to come and look at it if I was ever in doubt again.

Thank you, my friend, for teaching me to make up my mind and not settling for anything less.

PS: I had started to knit a throw for myself a day after I had completed the vest.

PS2: The throw is not knitted out of those two pure wool yarn rolls I had bought that winter. In fact, one of the rolls, the grey one, is now extinct due to the efforts of my cat.

Don’t talk! Not even if they are younger than you. Not even if they talk to you and jump at you, like those teenagers on Monday night.

It all started when my friend and I were discussing Friedrich Nietzsche just before midnight in the middle of an empty English street. Two teenaged males, naturally in hoodies, high on something way worse than alcohol, started jumping and yakking at us. Being a respectable girl as I am, I ignored them and made my friend do the same. The teens then proceeded to jump around the other members of our little company until they got cigarettes and learned our nationalities. And that’s when it all really started! In a matter of seconds I could hear my friend shouting: “I’m an international criminal lawyer!” and the teens screaming: “Yeah? Prove it!”

The next thing I remember was my friend running across a busy road, one of the teenagers running after him, the rest of us running after the teenager and the other teenager getting his friends with two fighting-type dogs to run after us… “I should call the police,” – I thought. And I honestly would if I didn’t have my hands busy with pulling my companions away from the barking dogs. It would also help to know where we were, you know, the address to give the police and so on. It all ended in a bus. All teenagers disappeared on the way to the bus stop, apart from the most persistent one. But he, too, was stopped from pursuing my friend to in the end. Oh, and police, which I called from the bus stop, had never shown up or rang back to take a statement…

Most people have school reunions, we have family ones. They happen almost as rarely - once every three years or so. And they happen separately - dad's family or mum's flat. The last one (with dad's family) was ... well, honest. For the first time, no one hid their emotions.

Why am I writing here about family stuff? Coz there are lots of grown-up kids in my boat. Don't let those who don't care about your heart into your heart. Don't lie to those who care. Don't try to be who you are not. Being who you are and being honest about it is the only way to be a happy family, to have a family. That's okay if they can't take it at first, give them some time, be true. If you have never wanted that job - say so, and go do something you've always wanted to do. If you have spent 10 years in the wrong profession - say so, don't waste another 90 in the same horror. If you have never been the person they thought you are - that happens, be gentle and be who you are. It takes two sides to listen and hear.

If any movie has a soul, then "Black Swan" is definitely one such kind. This film is a mixture of many ideas.

It's a tribute to the method of Stanislavski - a beautiful envisioning of how far an individual can reach in living through the role that is required... It's about loosing a mind whilst trying to acquire a new one - something that actors are required to do by the nature of their profession...

It's a tribute to ambiguity of a human soul - the evil and the pure, hiding within the same net of soul... 

And it's a tribute to being in the right place. The genius can only be achieved if one is doing what one was born to be doing, unable to do anything else,  driven by the power within to practice and practice to make excellence. But practice alone, of course, does not make a genius...

"One can run away from life, but not from death" (c)

It has been crazy for these past few days… If one doesn’t believe in coincidences, then one would notice that life’s trying to tell one something... Someone’s death – someone you don’t even know, but someone close enough through a circle of friends – might be on your Facebook news… You might offer your shoulder to those who are sobbing over the loss. And in the same time, life offers you a movie… by chance you find an old hard drive and stick it into your computer, go through the pile of films listed “to watch” not even by you but by another person and then you choose… I don’t know, perhaps, something like a “Hereafter”, and you spend an evening sobbing, too, unable to watch the movie without pausing to regain your breath…

And, all happening in the same segment of the past few days, life keeps throwing “communication of souls” into you, everywhere you look… Everything and everyone keeps repeating that art and writing are not only a physical, visual matter, but a communication of souls… And if you try to create the physical only, no communication happens, and the project does not fly. What are boundaries that souls have in their communication with each other? Can they talk when we are far away geographically? Over the Internet? Through a painting? In a story?

And how do you understand your subconscious – why does it pick on one specific theme and suffocates you until you pay attention? How to interpret this?

PS: I absolutely hated the Russian translation of the Hereafter (watched the French bits in Russian, the rest – in English) - it was... well, without a soul.

People tend to stare at each other with despise... Why? We howl like wolves because we are surrounded by wolves, but aren't we, ourselves, guilty of continuing the vicious circle? What if you tried to break the chain, today? Take to the extreme an idea of treating others the way you'd like to be treated yourself: pretend everyone around you is you.

At first, it might work out pretty well. Stuff might stop irritating you. You might laugh at the whistlers, let the pedestrians cross in front of your car, feel as if you are an Arabic lady in a yashmak, recognise the heaviness of the ladder that a guy is dragging across the pavement past your sleeping toddler... If you mute your judgement, you'll see that everyone around you is very much like you. No matter how stuck up their noses are or how submissive or young they may seem, they all have their own little habits, childhood fears, adult fears, they all care for SOMETHING!

So, it might be going really well, your little experiment, until this male with exaggerated body-parts walks by shooting his saliva onto the road... No way you want him to be you, no matter what he fears or cares for... You could probably associate with some murderers more than you could associate with these insensitive spitters!

But we can't just choose parts of the universe we want to identify with and parts we don't. We have to be able to see and accept the darkest inside ourselves in order to change it, to achieve inner growth and harmony. What power does a careless spit have over you? Nevertheless, here you are, stuck in the inability to be one with the world...

I have wanted to become a writer for a very long time. At some points in time - successful, at others - less so, I have produced some works, academic and fictional, that people had loved or criticised. Then a friend had posted an inspirational talk of a poet on my Facebook, and I absolutely adored it! The woman (the poet) advised to start with ten things I know to be true. So here is my list:

  1. I have walked over ten kilometers today.
  2. I have invented and cooked a lovely soup that I loved today.
  3. My cat is ginger and white.
  4. I am … [none of your business] years old.
  5. I am writing my first post here in quite a long time, but I really hope I will write more often, even though I have about 3 or 4 readers… Just for the discipline J
  6. I miss riding my bicycle, but am too lazy to do anything about it.
  7. I was very stressed about having to see those snobby people at my brother’s college on 1st and 2nd June, but feel much better now because I am going to play a mind game with them.
  8. I can’t force myself to clean my flat and have to stumble upon clothes, documents, lamps, staples, scissors, books, papers, boxes and pillows on my living room’s floor.
  9. I gathered all my courage together and went to my first meeting with this writer’s group today only to find out that the meeting was held yesterday, and that it is always held on Wednesdays, actually… (I double-checked, their website said Wednesday too...)
  10. I am absolutely knackered and need a good night’s sleep before an early start tomorrow…

What's your list?

Remembering is a weird thing. One moment we think we would remember this revelation forever, but years wipe away the details and the bleak reflections no longer seem real. Then reality (or different realities) comes back and strikes again, and this is when I remember why I chose to stop years ago. The reason I consciously chose ignorance over knowledge was my own peace of mind. The reason I remember this now is the return of anxiety and odd feeling of torment associated with lucid dreams. I am not stopping though, not this time. We can control our minds, conquer our fears and channel our willpower. We must learn to do this in order to step forward.

I do wonder what these blues are though. Every time I touch on something deeper than the material I feel this weird melancholy accompanied by a fear that if I don't watch a comedy and flip out of sadness immediately I would lose all that makes me happy and content in this physical life. Whether these emotions have any merits remains to be established - our minds like to play tricks on us, even our bodies can be in on the game. Surely spiritual development is a gain, not a loss... Yet for every step forward two seem to be taken back.

Just got back from a trip to Holland. I asked prosecutor in the Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia whether, from a legal point of view, it would ever be possible to prosecute current government in Russia for their atrocities in Chechnya in the same way as it's done in their Tribunal. He (the prosecutor) said that this would only be possible if the government changed, because Russia has power of veto, which would preclude Security Council from establishing a Tribunal that would prosecute Russia. That is why I find it both sad and funny that people are easily brainwashed by other people who pretend to be against the current government and say things like "don't go outside on demonstrations, give Moscow away to enemies as this is an effective step that was taken before in our history, instead collect materials that you can then take to court". Who gives a fuck about court? Basically, what's said is: "shut up, stop spoiling our holiday, you ignoramuses"...

Functions of the capital are divided between two cities in Holland: Amsterdam and Hague. Amsterdam is a party city while Hague hosts business, government buildings and international organisations. I personally didn't like Amster, it has a very aggressive atmosphere, too much sex and drugs (a lot of tourists come specifically for this, as prostitution and light drugs are legalised), and too many pushy people working on the streets of this city. We were literally running away from them when they either told us to pay 5 euros for taking a picture of their shop or wouldn't let us pass until we put some money in their hats... I was also a bit disappointed that it was illegal to take pics of prostitutes in the windows, however I totally understand their right to protect their body and all of that. Drugs such as marijuana and hashish are sold in local coffee shops on every corner (usually neighbouring with sex shops and sex museums :))). Center is safe, especially the Red Lights District (it is not the Street of Red Lights, like we are used to think of it in Ukraine and Russia, but actually an entire district that is 5 minutes walk from the central train station in the middle of Amsterdam). The safety is ensured by a large amount of police circling the streets. Architecture is truly beautiful, there are many channels and a huge number of cyclists. Bicycles are parked everywhere - sometimes one can find them lying tied together on the road! Hague, on the other hand, is a very calm, rich and quiet city with magnificent buildings and expensive establishments.

A couple of years ago I came to a fortune-teller. I was a broken and a depressed person stuck in my own problems. She told me: "Girl you better enjoy your life now, for these are your best days. You think it will get better, but the reality is it will only get worse". Every day I have lived since then has made my life better and me happier. Life is not what we expect it to be, it is not going to be the way we hope it would be, and it often was not the way we thought it was.

For some reason I am not great with this! Now is just another example of my every single essay writing practice - it is 4 am, and I have 12 hours before the deadline. Well, technically I have 13 hours before the deadline, but I have to finish by 4 pm to see Harry Potter... well, you do the math :) Why do I keep doing it, I wonder? What is it that I like? Maybe this panicky feeling of being an absolute looser and not being able to finish on time, or even worse - finishing on time but presenting a load of crap? I definitely like this increased brain capacity you get when there is like no time left... And these promises that this is the last essay I am starting 12 hours before submission. Promise. Next one will be better. Yeah, whatever. I don't even believe myself. 

On the bright side of life living in London has been great. LSE has hosted a speech of His Excellency Turk, the president of Slovenia. He was very inspiring but not informative due to his brilliant skills of diplomacy... :))) Great stuff, pips! Enjoy life!

I am no good at this material world. To me it is too big and frightening. And it hurts. "Scrutinise my best endeavour"... I KNOW  it isn't real... but chances are the world will be there tomorrow as it is now and I still wouldn't know how to deal with it.
